{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534826"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.11,0.13,0.53,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old Aboriginal man presents to Alice Springs Hospital Emergency Department with a three-week history of productive cough. He has recently commenced high-dose prednisolone for renal biopsy-proven focal segmental glomerulosclerosis alongside trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis. A five-day course of amoxicillin prescribed by his General Practitioner has not improved his symptoms. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 114/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. A chest X-ray is shown below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Upon confirmation of the likely diagnosis, which of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ceftriaxone + Azithromycin","Benzylpenicillin + Doxycycline","Vancomycin + Meropenem","Isoniazid + Rifampin + Ethambutol + Pyrazinamide","Surgical referral for right upper lobectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of pulmonary tuberculosis (TB). The clinical presentation includes chronic productive cough, fever, and constitutional symptoms in an immunocompromised Aboriginal patient from a region with higher TB prevalence. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoniazid + Rifampin + Ethambutol + Pyrazinamide\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard first-line treatment regimen for tuberculosis. This combination is recommended by the World Health Organisation and is effective against \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E. The intensive phase typically lasts two months, followed by a continuation phase with isoniazid and rifampicin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone + Azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an empiric regimen for severe community-acquired pneumonia. While this could cover typical bacterial pathogens, it would be ineffective against \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and inappropriate given the clinical presentation and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzylpenicillin + Doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is an empiric regimen for moderate community-acquired pneumonia. While this could cover typical bacterial pathogens, it would be ineffective against \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and inappropriate given the clinical presentation and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin + Meropenem\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad-spectrum regimen typically reserved for severe hospital-acquired infections or sepsis. While this patient is immunocompromised, this combination would not be effective against mycobacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical referral for right upper lobectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as initial management. While surgery may occasionally be required for complicated TB (such as drug-resistant cases or complications), medical therapy is always the first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recent initiation of high-dose prednisolone is a significant risk factor for TB reactivation. In regions with high TB prevalence, screening for latent TB prior to starting immunosuppression is recommended. The chronic nature of symptoms, failure to respond to standard antibiotics, and the patient\u0027s risk factors all support a likely diagnosis of TB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlongside medical management, appropriate infection control measures including airborne precautions and notification to the local public health unit/centre for disease control are essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immunosuppressed patients with upper lobe cavitating pneumonia should be investigated for pulmonary tuberculosis.","First-line treatment for tuberculosis consists of four drugs: isoniazid, rifampicin, ethambutol, and pyrazinamide.","High-dose corticosteroids increases the risk of tuberculosis reactivation.","Indigenous Australians living in Central Australia have higher rates of tuberculosis compared to non-Indigenous Australians."],"references":["Adigun R, Singh R. Tuberculosis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441916/","Tuberculosis (TB). In: Northern Territory Government | NT Health [Online]. Available from: https://health.nt.gov.au/public-health-notifiable-diseases/tuberculosis-tb","Transmission-Based Precautions. In: CDC Infection Control [Online]. Available from: https://www.cdc.gov/infection-control/hcp/basics/transmission-based-precautions.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21804"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21804"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CR9bcIiwVyP6butKRPS0k2pAOY9NY0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CR9bcIiwVyP6butKRPS0k2pAOY9NY0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":392,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T08:52:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T08:53:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96857"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2